{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe 2026-07-08 principal-architect audit (Reliability finding #3) found reconciler safety mechanisms that are implemented, tested, and **never called in production** - the safety they promise is illusory:\n\n1. **Create->label crash window double-creates Jira issues.** `dispatch_one.py:241-256` runs `create_issue` -> adds the `rebar-id:` label the JQL dedup keys on -> binds in memory only; bindings persist only at end of pass. A hard crash between create and label leaves an orphan issue invisible to dedup; the re-run duplicates it.\n2. **The write-ahead/recovery protocol is dead code - and miswired.** `bind_pending` has zero production callers, and `run_differs.py:351` passes the applier MODULE (no `search_issues`) to `recover_pending_bindings`, so real recovery `AttributeError`s into a fail-open swallow.\n3. **Crashed pass deadlocks reconciliation forever.** Lease `steal()` is implemented/tested (`_ref_lock.py:516-535`) but the held-ref path unconditionally exits 3 (`__main__.py:499-505`); after SIGKILL the remote `refs/reconciler/lock` persists until an operator hand-deletes it.\n4. **The REST-transport write path never retries transient HTTP failures.** `acli_rest.py:58-63` re-raises every `HTTPError` and `_call_with_retry` (`dispatch_one.py:100-144`) only catches `JiraAPIError`/`TimeoutError` - `urllib.error.HTTPError` is an `OSError`/`URLError` subclass it never catches, so the REST-transport writes get zero retry.\n\n**Transport map (verified, drives the whole design).** rebar's Jira client has TWO floors: the **REST floor** (`acli_rest.py`, raises raw `urllib.error.HTTPError`) and the **subprocess floor** (`acli_subprocess._run_acli`, raises `AcliMutationError`/`RetryExhaustedError`/`CalledProcessError`, NEVER `HTTPError`). Of the `_call_with_retry` call sites, only **four** route through REST and can raise `HTTPError`, and ALL FOUR are IDEMPOTENT writes: `dispatch_one.py:254` `set_entity_property`, `:483` `set_parent`, `:543` `update_issue` (priority/status/assignee legs), and `apply_inbound_records.py:181` `set_entity_property`. `create_issue`, `add_label`, `remove_label`, `add_comment`, `delete_issue`, `search_issues`, `get_issue`, `set_relationship` are ALL subprocess-floor. This has two consequences: (a) reviving HTTPError retry gives real resilience to exactly those four idempotent REST writes - retrying them needs NO dedup; (b) `create_issue` is NEVER retried by `_call_with_retry`, so a per-retry create dedup guard has no valid target - create's idempotency is provided by the write-ahead recovery (D1, cross-pass), the existing pre-create rebar-id JQL dedup (`dispatch_one.py:196`, in-pass), and C4's subprocess 429 loop (in-pass). Audit finding #2 is thus covered WITHOUT a new dedup guard.\n\n## What\n\nWire each mechanism into its intended call site, smallest-change-first (see Design decisions D1-D4, Sequencing, Findings triage).\n\n1. **Revive the retry layer WITHOUT a boundary translation.** Extend `_call_with_retry` (dispatch_one.py:100-144) to ALSO catch a retryable `urllib.error.HTTPError` in addition to `JiraAPIError`/`TimeoutError`, leaving acli_rest's raw-`HTTPError` raise UNCHANGED (the 8+ raw-HTTPError catchers rely on it). `HTTPError.code` 429 -> retry honoring `Retry-After` header when present, else ADR-0036 jittered backoff; 5xx -> jittered backoff; 4xx (incl. 404 on an absent entity property) -> re-raised raw immediately, mirroring the existing `400 <= status < 500` fast-fail branch (`dispatch_one.py:129`) so the absent-property 404 semantics are preserved. Backoff per ADR 0036: `2**(attempt+1) + rand[0,1)` s, capped 60s; max_retries=3. Because `_call_with_retry` is re-exported via `batch_dispatch` and imported by `apply_outbound.py`/`apply_inbound.py`/`apply_inbound_records.py`, this uniformly benefits every call site (intended - `apply_inbound_records.py:181`'s `set_entity_property` is one of the four REST beneficiaries); those modules need no edits and their existing tests must stay green.\n2. **Deterministic write-ahead recovery (D1).** Persist `bind_pending` BEFORE `create_issue`; on the returned key, `record_pending_key(local_id, jira_key)` and persist AGAIN BEFORE `add_label`. Hoist the `AcliClient` (built at run_differs.py:393) ABOVE the recovery call; pass it (not the applier module) to `recover_pending_bindings`. LOUD failures: `alert_store` bridge alert + a nonzero `recovery_failures` pass tally.\n3. **Comments single-attempt (D2).** Unwrap `add_comment` from `_call_with_retry` at `dispatch_one.py:341` (create path) and `:610` (update path) -> single-attempt bare call feeding the existing non-fatal `comment_errors` list.\n4. **Crashed-pass lease steal (D3).** In `__main__.py`'s held-lock path, attempt `steal()` instead of unconditional exit 3, behind kill-switch `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` (default ON).\n\n(No per-retry create dedup guard and no `acli.py` search-cache change - see the transport-map rationale above; create is not retried at this layer.)\n\n## Scope\n\nIn:\n- `dispatch_one.py`: `_call_with_retry` gains an `except urllib.error.HTTPError` clause (429 Retry-After/backoff, 5xx backoff, 4xx incl. 404 fast-fail; ADR-0036 formula); `bind_pending`+persist before create, `record_pending_key`+persist after create/before label; **unwrap `add_comment` from `_call_with_retry` at BOTH `:341` and `:610`** -> single-attempt bare call feeding `comment_errors` (D2).\n- `run_differs.py`: hoist the `AcliClient` above the recovery call; pass it to `recover_pending_bindings` with a `failure_sink` list; emit an `alert_store` alert per failure; set `ctx.recovery_failures = len(failure_sink)` (see D4 for the channel).\n- `binding_store.py`: add `record_pending_key(local_id, jira_key) -> None` (sets `jira_key` on an existing pending entry, keeps `state='pending'`, `save()`s); add a `BindingPersistError`; extend `recover_pending_bindings(client, *, failure_sink: list[dict] | None = None) -> int` (**return type stays `int`** - existing `test_binding_store.py` int assertions unaffected) with the deterministic branch (confirm a keyed-pending record with NO Jira search; keyless -> `search_issues` fallback; append `{local_id, reason}` to `failure_sink` on error); update the module docstring for the keyed-pending invariant.\n- `reconcile.py`: read `ctx.recovery_failures` into the pass `result` dict (beside `mutation_failures`) and the `sync_pass_end` log.\n- `__main__.py`: hoist `pass_id` generation ABOVE the `check_pass_lock` block (so it is the `steal()` holder); held-lock path calls `steal_pass_lock` and, on a steal-win, sets `acquired=True`, threads the new oid into `lock_oid`, starts the heartbeat, and SKIPS the unconditional `acquire_pass_lock`; add the `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` kill-switch.\n- `_advisory_lock.py`: thin `steal_pass_lock(holder, repo_root, *, sleep_fn=time.sleep) -> str | None` wrapping `_ref_lock.steal(...)`; on an unexpected exception from `steal()` (git transport/permission error), it is caught, logged, and treated as \"not stolen\" (fail-closed -> exit 3), never crashing the pass.\n- `docs/env-vars.md` + the env registry: register `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` (run the `gen_env_registry.py` generator) so the CI env-drift gate stays green.\n- Tests: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/` (retry/write-ahead/recovery/steal/comment) and `tests/scripts/bridge/`.\n\nRead-only (relied on, not changed): `acli_rest.py` (raw HTTPError raise UNCHANGED); `_ref_lock.py` (`steal()` already implemented); `apply_outbound.py`/`apply_inbound.py`/`apply_inbound_records.py` (inherit the `_call_with_retry` HTTPError behavior uniformly - existing tests must stay green).\n\nOut (justified): bulk-path 429 + `_call_with_backoff` (C4); inbound status mapping (audit-remediation epic). Deferred with rationale (Findings triage): unresolvable-pending TTL; live E2E run; `recovery_failures` as an exit gate.\n\n## Design decisions (resolved from code facts)\n\n- **D1 - create->label window closed DETERMINISTICALLY.** acli `create_issue` cannot carry the rebar-id label atomically (`--labels` is a destructive SET-REPLACE). Instead the pending binding records the `jira_key` the instant `create_issue` returns (persisted before `add_label`), so `recover_pending_bindings` confirms a keyed pending record with NO Jira search. Only a keyless pending record uses the label `search_issues` fallback. **Persist-failure is ITEM-SCOPED:** `bind_pending`/`record_pending_key` persist failure raises `BindingPersistError`, `create_issue` is then NOT called for that mutation, the mutation outcome gets an `error` key (which increments `mutation_failures` via the existing outcome accounting) and an `alert_store` alert is emitted; the pass CONTINUES with remaining mutations. **keyed-pending is a SUB-state, not a new ADR-0027 state:** the record stays `state='pending'` (the ADR-0027 enumerated state) with an additive `jira_key` field populated - it does NOT add a fourth state to `pending|confirmed|retired`, so ADR 0027's state machine is unchanged (the module docstring records the sub-state). **Rollback semantics (accurate):** rolling back to the pre-plan reconciler causes NO store corruption (a keyed-pending is a valid pending shape; old code ignores the extra `jira_key` field), BUT the old code FORFEITS the new deterministic protection for any record currently in the create->label window - it label-searches, misses (the label is not yet attached in that exact window), and unbinds -> the create is re-attempted next pass (the pre-existing duplicate risk this ticket removes). So rollback is safe but re-exposes the original window; it does not create a new failure mode.\n- **D2 - comments scoped OUT of the retry guard.** No cheap Jira-side idempotency key exists for a comment (posted verbatim through the `acli_subprocess` floor), and a duplicate comment is low-harm vs. a duplicate issue; a visible `[rebar-cid]` trailer would pollute every synced comment. So `add_comment` is unwrapped from `_call_with_retry` at `dispatch_one.py:341` AND `:610` and posted SINGLE-attempt; a failed post appends to `comment_errors` and is re-emitted by the comment differ next pass (eventually-consistent). The real failure `add_comment` raises is `AcliMutationError`/`RetryExhaustedError` (subprocess floor), NOT `HTTPError` - the test injects that real type and asserts exactly one call.\n- **D3 - lease expiry uses `steal()` itself.** `_ref_lock` treats `heartbeat_ns` as diagnostic-only and determines expiry behaviorally via `steal()` (read -> sleep one `lease_secs` -> re-check `(oid,fence)` progress). The held-lock path calls `advisory.steal_pass_lock(pass_id, repo_root)`, whose None-return discrimination protocol is documented ON the wrapper (co-located, not only in the caller):\n  - **new oid** -> stale lease STOLEN: set `acquired=True`, thread the new oid into `lock_oid`, START the heartbeat against it (mirroring `__main__.py:544-549`), SKIP the unconditional `acquire_pass_lock`, proceed.\n  - **None** -> re-read the ref: **still held** (live holder) -> **exit 3**; **freed** (holder released during our sleep) -> normal `acquire_pass_lock` (won -> proceed; lost to a racer -> exit 3).\n  - **`steal()` raises** (git transport/permission error) -> caught in the wrapper, logged, treated as not-stolen -> **exit 3** (fail-closed, never crashes the pass).\n  `pass_id` is generated BEFORE the lock check so it is the steal `holder`. Steal sleeps one `lock_lease_secs` (default 120s); a structured log is emitted at the START of the sleep and on a successful steal (prior holder + new oid, `lease_steal` event); `sleep_fn` is injected in tests. The whole branch is behind `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` (default ON) - OFF reverts to unconditional exit-3 (ops back-out, tested).\n- **D4 - `recovery_failures` threading via ctx (run_differs returns None).** `run_differs_mod.run_differs(ctx, ...)` is a procedure that populates `ctx` and returns `None`, so the count is threaded on the context object, NOT a return value: `recover_pending_bindings(client, *, failure_sink=None) -> int` KEEPS its `int` return (recovered count) and appends failures to the caller-supplied `failure_sink`; `run_differs` sets `ctx.recovery_failures = len(failure_sink)`; `reconcile.py` reads `ctx.recovery_failures` into the `result` dict (beside `mutation_failures`) and `sync_pass_end`. Observability-only, intentionally NOT wired into `__main__.py`'s `mutation_failures` exit gate (`:345`): recovery is best-effort/fail-open, so a transient Jira search hiccup must not fail an otherwise-clean pass.\n\n## Sequencing (one change, addresses decomposition finding)\n\nThe four fixes are the single \"revive the dead reconciler safety machinery\" workstream from the audit; each has its OWN independent unit test and none depends on another's runtime, but they share one small reconciler test surface and overlap in `dispatch_one.py` (retry + write-ahead + comment-unwrap). Landing them as one Gerrit change avoids four near-trivial stacked changes with repeated rebase/review overhead; each AC is independently verifiable. Fix 4 is additionally behind its own kill-switch, disable-able in production independent of the others.\n\n## Findings triage (deferrals justified)\n\n- **Unresolvable-pending TTL/retirement** (0.264): DEFERRED to a discovered-from follow-up; a pending record that cannot resolve stays pending and re-alerts each pass (24h-deduped).\n- **Live end-to-end AC** (0.0): DEFERRED - this ticket is code-only per the epic decomposition; live exercise is owned by sibling D1 (close-ferreous-cardinal) + the reconcile-bridge GHA.\n- **`recovery_failures` exit gate** (0.0): INTENTIONAL non-gate - see D4.\n- **Kill-switches for fixes 1-3** (0.0): fix 1 (HTTPError retry) only ADDS retries to previously-unretried idempotent REST writes (strictly safer, no behavior inversion); fix 2 (write-ahead) and fix 3 (comment-unwrap) change failure-path behavior only. A revert-by-commit is the back-out for these; only fix 4 (held-lock behavior inversion on a critical path) warrants a runtime kill-switch, which it has.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `_call_with_retry` retries a retryable `HTTPError`: `code` 429 honoring `Retry-After` when PRESENT, else jittered backoff (`2**(attempt+1)+rand[0,1)`, cap 60s); 5xx with the same backoff; non-retryable 4xx (incl. 404) re-raised raw - WITHOUT translating at `acli_rest.py`, a test asserts the raw `HTTPError` raise from `acli_rest` is unchanged so raw-`HTTPError` catchers (e.g. apply_handlers.py:151's 404) still see raw `HTTPError`. Both header-present and header-absent 429 paths, a 5xx, and a fast-failed 404 are tested. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_retry_httperror.py`.\n- [ ] Write-ahead is deterministic (D1): `bind_pending` persisted BEFORE `create_issue`; `record_pending_key` persisted BEFORE `add_label`. `recover_pending_bindings` confirms any keyed-pending record (retro-attaching the label idempotently) with NO Jira search -> crash between create and label yields NO duplicate; keyless pending falls back to `search_issues` (confirm if found, else unbind). Tests: (a) crash after create+key-persist, before label -> next pass confirms, no duplicate; (b) crash before create -> fallback unbind; (c) `bind_pending`/`record_pending_key` persist failure raises `BindingPersistError`, **`create_issue` is asserted NOT called**, the mutation is recorded failed (mutation_failures increments) + an `alert_store` alert fires, and the pass continues. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_write_ahead_recovery.py`.\n- [ ] `recover_pending_bindings` receives the hoisted `AcliClient` (exposing `search_issues`, not the applier module) and a `failure_sink` list (its `int` return unchanged); a recovery failure appends to `failure_sink`, emits an `alert_store` bridge alert, AND surfaces a nonzero `recovery_failures` (via `ctx.recovery_failures`) on the pass `result` + `sync_pass_end` log, instead of the silent swallow. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_recovery_loud_failures.py`.\n- [ ] Comments post single-attempt (D2): `add_comment` is unwrapped from `_call_with_retry` at BOTH `:341` and `:610`; a test injects `AcliMutationError`/`RetryExhaustedError` on `add_comment` and asserts it is called EXACTLY once and recorded to `comment_errors` (no duplicate post). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_comment_single_attempt.py`.\n- [ ] Held-lock path (D3, behind `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL`) - FIVE test cases with injected `sleep_fn`: (1) steal returns new oid -> `acquired=True`, oid threaded into `lock_oid`, heartbeat started, acquire skipped, proceed; (2) None + still-held -> exit 3; (3a) None + freed + acquire wins -> proceed; (3b) None + freed + acquire lost -> exit 3; (4) kill-switch OFF -> unconditional exit 3 (no steal attempted). `steal()` raising is covered too (-> exit 3, no crash). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_lock_steal.py`.\n- [ ] `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` is registered in `docs/env-vars.md` via the env registry so the CI env-drift gate passes.\n- [ ] Both test locations green: `python -m pytest tests/scripts/bridge/ -q` AND `python -m pytest tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/ -q`.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783574876424580001,"uuid":"415841b4-c08a-47d3-8dfd-97cc7d3ba865"}